{{Infobox person | name = Michelle Mohabeer | birth_date = 1961 | birth_place = Guyana, South America }} '''Michelle Mohabeer''' is a [[Canadians|Canadian]] [[filmmaker]] and [[Film writer|writer]].<ref name=":5" /> Her films have received many rewards including the Isabella Liddell Art Award,<ref name=":13">http://aafilmfest.org/images/pdfs/festival-programs/aaff_32_program.pdf</ref> and the 5 Feminist Minutes Award.<ref>{{Citation|last=Baker|first=Marie Annharte|title=Five Feminist Minutes|date=2000-01-01|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0280677/fullcredits?ref_=tt_ov_dr#directors|last2=Blain|last3=Boschman|last4=Browne|last5=Burns|last6=Cole|last7=Dempsey|last8=Fleming|last9=Gagnon|first2=Kim|first3=Lorna|first4=Christene|first5=Alison|first6=Janis|first7=Shawna|first8=Ann Marie|first9=Angèle|accessdate=2016-10-26}}</ref> Her first work, ''Exposure'' (1990) was produced through the [[National Film Board of Canada|National Film Board]]'s [[Studio D]].<ref name=":5" /><ref name=":1" /> During and after creating several films, she has also served as an adjunct lecturer at the following post-secondary institutions: [[University of Toronto]], [[Trent University]], [[University of Western Ontario]], [[Ryerson University]] and [[Sheridan College]].<ref name=":2">{{Cite web|url=http://www.vtape.org/artist?ai=701|title=Michelle Mohabeer|last=|first=|date=|website=Vtape|publisher=|access-date=2016-10-10}}</ref>
Michelle's film work has been displayed at over 150 [[Film festival|festivals]], conferences and [[Art Gallery|galleries]] located across 18 countries from multiple continents. Her films have been collected by over sixty [[university]] [[Library|libraries]] across [[North America]], the [[Caribbean]] and [[Australia]].<ref name=":1" /><ref name=":2" />
== Early life and education == Michelle Mohabeer was born in [[Guyana]], [[South America]] in 1961.<ref name=":5">{{Cite book|title=The Romance of Transgression in Canada: Queering Sexualities,|last=Waugh|first=Thomas|publisher=McGill-Queen's University Press|year=2006|isbn=9780773530690|location=Montreal, QU|pages=127, 155, 172, 472|via=Print}}</ref> She moved to [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]], Canada in 1974 at the age of 13.<ref name=":6">{{Cite book|title=Film Fatales: Independent Women Directors|last=Redding|first=Judith M.|last2=Brownworth|first2=Victoria A.|publisher=Seal Press|year=1997|isbn=1-878067-97-4|location=Seattle, WA|pages=104–108|via=Print}}</ref> In 1986, she successfully received her [[Bachelor's degree|BA]] in [[Film studies|Film Studies]] from [[Carleton University]]. Her second degree was earned in 1998, it was a [[Master of Fine Arts|Master's of Fine Arts]] in [[Film production|Film Production]] from [[York University]].<ref name=":5" /><ref name=":6" /> In 2005, at the University of Toronto she received a PhD in Culture and Communication with a focus on Film Studies.<ref name=":1">{{Cite web|url=http://www.cfmdc.org/user/8430|title=Michelle Mohabeer|last=|first=|date=|website=CFMDC - Canadian Filmmakers Distribution Centre|publisher=|access-date=2016-10-10}}</ref>
== Career == Michelle Mohabeer started her film-making career working for the National Film Board in Studio D,<ref name=":1" /> she created her first short film ''Exposure'' (1990) for the series ''Five Feminist Minutes''. This film was a huge success, not only for its content, but for the fact that this was "the first up-front [[lesbian]] film from the NFB" and the fact that the film was made by, in the words of Film Critic Thomas Waugh, "lesbian artist of colour in the Canadian canon."<ref name=":5" /> Following the release of her film she had a brief employment with [[CKLN-FM|CKLN]] [[radio]].<ref name=":1" /> Four years later she released her second film ''Coconut/Cane & Cutlass'' (1994); due to the great success of her first film the budget for her second feature was almost nine times larger allowing her to shoot in Canada and Guyana. In 1996, she created two more films ''Two/Doh'' and ''Child-play'' (1997); ''Two/Doh'' was noted for being produced at very low cost, while ''Child-play'' was Mohabeer's first attempt at a drama film.<ref name=":6" /> During the nineteen-nineties she was active on several arts community boards in Toronto, frequently serving as [[Arts administrator|administrator]].<ref name=":1" />
In the new millennium, Michelle Mohabeer directed several more films, in 2001 she created the film ''Tracing Soul''; in 2003 she wrote and directed the film ''Echoes''. Finally, in 2008, she made the film ''Blu In You.'' <ref name=":2" /><ref name=":0">{{Cite news|url=http://www.bfi.org.uk/films-tv-people/4ce2bab3f1bec|title=Michelle Mohabeer|newspaper=BFI|access-date=2016-10-10}}</ref>
Throughout her career as a filmmaker Professor Mohabeer has also taught the next generation of filmmakers, she has appeared as a [[guest lecturer]] or hosted workshops at several post-secondary institutions. She has also taught entire classes, namely Film Studies at [[Innis College, Toronto|Innis College]], [[Cinema Studies]] at the University of Toronto, and York University and Film Production at Ryerson University.<ref name=":1" /> Currently, Professor Mohabeer teaches in the [[Communication studies|Communication Studies]] and [[Humanities]] departments at [[York University]].<ref name=":2" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://yorku.academia.edu/MichelleMohabeer|title=Michelle Mohabeer {{!}} York University - Academia.edu|last=|first=|date=|website=yorku.academia.edu|publisher=|access-date=2016-10-14}}</ref>
== Cinematic style and influence == Many critics have noted that Mohabeer's films frequently explore the themes of "the diversity of cultural identity and the [[politics]] of [[gender]], [[Human sexuality|sexuality]] and [[colonialism]]."<ref name=":6" /> Film Scholar Tara Atluri, has argued that Mohabeer's films also feature several links to the [[Indo-Caribbean]] film [[tradition]].<ref name=":7">{{Cite journal|last=Atluri|first=Tara|year=2009|title=Putting the ‘Cool’ in Coolie: Disidentification, Desire and Dissent in the Work of Filmmaker Michelle Mohabeer.|url=http://www.uwispace.sta.uwi.edu/dspace/bitstream/handle/2139/15939/T.%20Atluri-%20Putting%20the%20Cool%20in%20Coolie.pdf?sequence=1&isAllowed=y|journal=Caribbean Review of Gender Studies|volume=|issue=3|pages=1–25|access-date=2016-10-10}}</ref>
== Filmography == {| class="wikitable" !Year !Title !Credit Listing !Description |- |1990 |Exposure |Filmmaker,<ref name=":0" /> Researcher, Scriptwriter, Director<ref name=":16">{{Cite web|url=http://people.wcsu.edu/mccarneyh/fva/M/mohabeerCV.pdf|title=Michelle Angela Mohabeer (PhD)|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=2016-11-12}}</ref> |[[Experimental film|Experimental documentary]] on the issues of race and [[racism]], sexuality and [[homophobia]], [[Cultural identity|cultural]] and [[ethnic identity]].<ref name=":6" /><ref name=":8">{{Cite web|url=http://www.cfmdc.org/node/522|title=Exposure|last=|first=|date=|website=CFMDC - Canadian Filmmakers Distribution Centre|publisher=|access-date=2016-10-14}}</ref> |- |1994 |Coconut/Cane & Cutlass |Scriptwriter, Director, Producer<ref name=":16" /> |[[Poetry|Poetic]] thoughts on exile, displacement and nationhood from an Indo-Caribbean lesbian [[immigrant]]; "raising many questions about the confluence of culture and sexuality."<ref name=":6" /><ref name=":7" /> This film contains elements of an [[autobiography]], a historical documentary and an experimental film; represented with the use of landscape, histories, archived images, voices, theatrical dances and movement scenes, all of which are poetically fragmented.<ref name=":5" /><ref name=":9">{{Cite web|url=http://www.cfmdc.org/node/375|title=Coconut/Cane & Cutlass|last=|first=|date=|website=CFMDC - Canadian Filmmakers Distribution Centre|publisher=|access-date=2016-10-14}}</ref> Film critic Thomas Waugh has described this film as a "lush and complex first-person essay on lesbian desire and [[genealogy]] in the context of [[Postcolonialism|postcolonial]] exile."<ref name=":5" /> |- |1996 |Two/Doh | |Poetic pastiche about the intersection of cultural and erotic connections between women of different cultural origins.<ref name=":5" /><ref name=":10">{{Cite web|url=http://www.cfmdc.org/node/1465|title=Two/Doh|last=|first=|date=|website=CFMDC - Canadian Fil